types of transformation - 
1. narrow transformation = transformation doesn't inculdes multiple partitions while execution -- so no shuffle data b/w partition hence this are faster
        eg - map(), filter(), select()

2. wide transformation = transformation does inculdes multiple partitions while execution
        eg - groupby(), joins, coalesce, repartition 

---------------------------------------------
different partitions methods in databricks - 
1. repartition = used to increase or decrease number the partitions 
                df.rdd.getNumPartitions() --> return number of partitions in df dataframe
                df.repartition(24)

2. coalesce = used only to decrease num of partition -- repartition also do the same but coalesce will try to avoid shuffling, 
how it avoid shuffle -- when it try to reduce partitons it will try to reduce with in same executor
        Imagine you have 8 partitions → want 4 partitions
        With coalesce(4):
        Spark will:
        combine nearby partitions
        assign multiple old partitions → one new partition
        Data stays mostly on the same executor
-- FYI, instead executor we have multiple paritions/tasks
for more info refer image --> inteview prepartion\images\coalesce and repartition.png

3. Hash partition = this is the method which decide which row need to move to which partition while join, groupBy, distrinct,repartition etc
        When you do something like:
        df.repartition(3, "key")
        👉 Spark does NOT randomly distribute data
        👉 It uses a hash function on the key column

        How it works step-by-step:
        1. Take the column value (example: A, B, C)
        2. Apply a hash function
        Do:
        partition_id = hash(key) % number_of_partitions
        3. Based on result → data goes to that partition

🔥 Why this is IMPORTANT
This is VERY critical for joins and groupBy:
All same keys are in same partition
So Spark can:
do local processing
avoid unnecessary shuffles later

example--
                Input Data
        -------------------------
        (A,10) (B,20) (C,30)
        (A,30) (B,50)
        -------------------------

                  │
                  ▼
         Apply Hash Function
     partition = hash(key) % 3
                  │
                  ▼

        -------------------------
        |       |       |       |
        ▼       ▼       ▼       ▼

   Partition 0   Partition 1   Partition 2
   -----------   -----------   -----------
   (A,10)        (B,20)        (C,30)
   (A,30)        (B,50)

4. Range partition(value based) = data is splted based on values 
        eg -- 
        1 -> 100 into p1
        101 -> 200 into p2
        201 -> 300 into p3
df = df.repartitionByRange(100,"order_date")
used for sorting, windown functions...

5. round-robin partitioning(even distrubution) = spark distributes rows evenly and sequentinally
        consider we have 3 partitions
        row1 --> p1, row2 --> p2, row3 --> p3
        row4 --> p1, row5 --> p2, row6 --> p3
df = df.repartition(3)
used for load balancing, remove skew, parallel write

6. bucketing = pre-dividing data into fixed number of files (buckets) based on a column (using hash)

        When you write a table with bucketing:
        df.write.bucketBy(4, "id").saveAsTable("table1")

        Spark does:
        bucket_id = hash(id) % 4
        👉 and stores data into 4 bucket files

        🔹 Simple Example

                Data:
                (A,10), (B,20), (A,30), (C,40)
                Bucket count = 3
                Assume:
                hash(A)%3 = 0
                hash(B)%3 = 1
                hash(C)%3 = 2

                Stored as:
                Bucket 0 → (A,10), (A,30)
                Bucket 1 → (B,20)
                Bucket 2 → (C,40)
                👉 This happens at write time, not during 

        🔹 How Bucketing reduces shuffle

                Now imagine you have two tables bucketed on same column and same number of buckets

                table1 → bucketBy(4, "id")
                table2 → bucketBy(4, "id")
                ❌ Without Bucketing (Normal Join)
                table1 → random partitions
                table2 → random partitions

                👉 Spark must:

                shuffle table1
                shuffle table2
                Shuffle → bring same keys together
                ✅ With Bucketing
                table1 bucket 0 → id=A
                table2 bucket 0 → id=A

                table1 bucket 1 → id=B
                table2 bucket 1 → id=B

                👉 Data is already aligned

                So Spark can do:
                Bucket 0 ↔ Bucket 0
                Bucket 1 ↔ Bucket 1

                🚀 No full shuffle required

        Bucketing does not completely eliminate shuffle always, but it significantly reduces it

